00:21:02.719 --> 00:21:07.359
really nice way to work. You have one notebook that you tweak until you've got a really nice

00:21:07.359 --> 00:21:16.959
report. You can render to one or many formats. So I showed you rendering to PDFs, but you might

00:21:16.959 --> 00:21:23.599
use the same notebook to render to PDF and HTML. And it's really sort of you do you automation,

00:21:23.599 --> 00:21:29.599
right? You have to call that Korto render many times if you want to do it with many values of

00:21:29.599 --> 00:21:34.640
the parameter. But there's lots of ways to do that. And it's sort of you do the way you'd like

00:21:34.640 --> 00:21:41.839
to do it. There are lots of other things that I kind of haven't been able to talk about but are

00:21:41.839 --> 00:21:48.079
or work great with parameterized reporting. So tables work great. For instance, tables that come

00:21:48.079 --> 00:21:52.319
out of the great tables package work great with Korto. They work great in these kind of reports.

00:21:53.040 --> 00:22:00.000
There's a thing called the include short code. And that is a way to include other, for example,

00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:07.199
markdown files in your notebook without like basically if you don't want to have a ton of

00:22:07.199 --> 00:22:11.839
markdown in your notebook, you can use this just to pull in that markdown content from somewhere

00:22:11.839 --> 00:22:17.760
else. There's also this thing called the contents short code that just lets you rearrange content.

00:22:18.319 --> 00:22:24.319
The biggest use case for that is you have a code cell that creates some output rather than having

00:22:24.319 --> 00:22:28.719
it show up just where you put that code cell. You can take that output and put it somewhere else.

00:22:28.719 --> 00:22:32.880
And often that means in the markdown cell you want to include it there.

00:22:34.880 --> 00:22:40.400
You can also show content conditional on format. So if you're doing two versions of a report,

00:22:40.400 --> 00:22:45.920
one that goes to HTML and one that goes to PDF, you might want different things. So it might be

00:22:45.920 --> 00:22:53.040
that you want some kind of interactive plot in your HTML version versus just a static plot in

00:22:53.040 --> 00:22:59.920
the PDF version. So there's a way to have those objects only show up in one format while still

00:22:59.920 --> 00:23:07.040
using that one notebook. And then everything I've shown you has been using a Jupyter notebook as the

00:23:07.040 --> 00:23:15.839
source document. But Korto also has a plain text format that has an extension .qmd. It's a variant

00:23:15.839 --> 00:23:21.199
of markdown. The great thing about that is that it's much easier to use version control with.

00:23:21.199 --> 00:23:24.880
It's much easier to copy and paste examples if you're trying to teach people about it.

00:23:25.920 --> 00:23:33.599
So if that exists, consider it. And that's all I have. So thank you very much. There's some links

00:23:33.599 --> 00:23:39.280
here about how to get started with Korto, where to find these examples. If you've got general Korto

00:23:39.280 --> 00:23:44.880
questions, the GitHub discussion is a great place to ask them. If you have anything here you want

00:23:44.880 --> 00:23:52.880
to ask me, feel free to email me. A big thanks again to JD Ryan for her inspiring example. And

00:23:52.880 --> 00:24:01.280
she gave a talk a couple of years ago that is a great way to see if you want to see how this looks

00:24:01.359 --> 00:24:03.839
in the R ecosystem. So thank you.

00:24:10.959 --> 00:24:16.239
Okay. Excellent talk. We have quite a few questions that are in the Slack. And so

00:24:16.800 --> 00:24:22.560
for those of you joining, please go ahead and reply to the talk announcement in the

00:24:22.560 --> 00:24:28.479
track general channel with any questions you might have. Going by emoji responses,

00:24:29.119 --> 00:24:34.400
we have a question from Ariana. So in this example, you show simple operations like

00:24:34.400 --> 00:24:40.239
filtering and access labeling as your parameterization. But can you parameterize

00:24:40.239 --> 00:24:45.199
more complex operations like using an entirely different dataset or running a model with

00:24:45.199 --> 00:24:52.319
maybe multiple different tuning parameters? Yes. I think the answer is yes. I kept this

00:24:52.319 --> 00:24:59.199
example intentionally simple so you could see how it sort of looks. But anything that you can

00:24:59.199 --> 00:25:06.079
translate to a single variable value could be a parameter. It could be many parameters. So,

00:25:06.800 --> 00:25:12.160
yes. I think is the answer. And we also have a question from Jay.

00:25:13.119 --> 00:25:17.760
When previously trying to parameterize reports like this, I struggled to use the parameter in

00:25:17.760 --> 00:25:23.040
the YAML metadata. For example, getting the metadata title to be Corvallis and Portland.

00:25:23.920 --> 00:25:29.040
Is something like that possible? That is an excellent question and something

00:25:29.040 --> 00:25:34.239
I also struggled with. There are some fields in the YAML metadata that you cannot use a

00:25:34.239 --> 00:25:42.079
parameter in because it gets processed before the computation happens. So you sort of saw

00:25:42.079 --> 00:25:46.079
one approach here. The approach with the header was to just find a different way to set the

00:25:46.079 --> 00:25:51.680
title. You can set titles by setting level one markdown headers. That's one approach.

00:25:53.040 --> 00:25:58.400
There is another possibility where you can actually create YAML blocks. You can have more

00:25:58.400 --> 00:26:07.119
than one YAML block in your document. So it's possible that you could create another YAML block.

00:26:07.119 --> 00:26:13.119
But again, it depends. Some of these things Cordo just processes before you hit the computation.

00:26:14.079 --> 00:26:17.439
So it depends. Depends on the actual option.

00:26:19.520 --> 00:26:24.479
This is a question for me. You mentioned that you built this talk with Cordo. Very cool.

00:26:25.439 --> 00:26:31.359
You showed also the Cordo render. But I also happen to know that there is a Cordo serve.

00:26:31.920 --> 00:26:38.400
So if you're building a slide deck like this, can you use Cordo serve to render your talk live in

00:26:38.400 --> 00:26:44.079
the browser while you're writing it? Or can you only generate the slides statically afterwards

00:26:44.079 --> 00:26:48.400
with Cordo render? I only showed you Cordo render.

00:26:51.920 --> 00:26:56.479
In this instance, Cordo serve and Cordo preview would do the same thing. I tend to use Cordo

00:26:56.479 --> 00:27:05.599
preview because the Cordo extension and VS code has a preview shortcut. And yes, that's exactly

00:27:05.599 --> 00:27:11.040
how you use it. So when I'm working on my slides, I did these in a QMD. So I had that open. I was

00:27:11.040 --> 00:27:19.680
running Cordo preview. And there's a setting where it will render on save. So I'm actively editing

00:27:19.680 --> 00:27:25.680
the slides, hit save, the preview of the slides updates instantly. Almost instantly.

00:27:26.319 --> 00:27:38.160
Very cool. Okay. So going down the list now, we have a question from Lauren. Does Cordo have a

00:27:38.160 --> 00:27:43.920
way to render to HTML that is specifically formatted for email? I don't know if I've heard

00:27:43.920 --> 00:27:53.599
that before. Yeah. It does. With a very large caveat. And that caveat is that it's designed

00:27:53.599 --> 00:27:58.959
for emails that will be sent in Posit Connect, which is one of Posit's professional products.

00:28:01.920 --> 00:28:07.680
And then we've got a question from Kadar. Is the Cordo CLI installation necessary

00:28:07.680 --> 00:28:18.239
before you can use Cordo inside of notebooks? Yes. Yeah. It is. But there's more than one way

00:28:18.239 --> 00:28:25.040
to get it, right? You can go to Cordo.org and grab an installer. It's also available through

00:28:25.040 --> 00:28:31.119
pip. So you can pip install Cordo CLI. I think also Conda Forge?

00:28:31.119 --> 00:28:32.239
Yes. Yeah. Awesome.

00:28:36.079 --> 00:28:45.359
Okay. Joshua asks, can Cordo also render ordinary markdown.md files? And what about collections of

00:28:45.359 --> 00:28:50.479
markdown and IPython notebook files that make a single document?

00:28:52.239 --> 00:28:57.839
Was the last part into a single document? I think that's what it was intended to mean.

00:28:57.839 --> 00:29:04.319
Like, so can you take a collection of multiple, like, markdown or I think it actually has to be

00:29:04.319 --> 00:29:12.000
like Q markdown files and IPYMB files and make those into a single document. So, like, taking

00:29:12.000 --> 00:29:17.680
multiple inputs. Yeah. So, okay. Let me answer those in part. So, you can definitely use Cordo

00:29:17.680 --> 00:29:26.239
to render a .md, like a plain markdown document, for sure. You can have a project that mixes

00:29:26.800 --> 00:29:30.479
markdown and Python notebooks, and Cordo will be happy with that.

00:29:33.359 --> 00:29:37.920
If you want to get them all into a single document, that's where things may get more

00:29:37.920 --> 00:29:44.400
complicated. You can certainly render them all into a single website where those documents are

00:29:44.400 --> 00:29:49.439
separate pages. It will be a little bit more work to make them all into a single page.

00:29:50.640 --> 00:29:56.800
Okay. Great. So, there's still a few more questions, but unfortunately we are at time. So,

00:29:58.079 --> 00:30:02.719
maybe you can jump in the Slack and answer those if you have any time. But let's thank

00:30:02.719 --> 00:30:08.880
Charlotte once again for a fantastic talk.

